The National Diet Library NDL Kokuritsu Kokkai Toshokan the national library Japan and among the largest libraries the world was established 1948 for the purpose assisting members the National Diet Japan Kokkai researching matters public policy The library similar purpose and scope the United States Library Congress The National Diet Library NDL consists two main facilities Tokyo and Kyoto and several other branch libraries throughout Japan The National Diet Library the successor three separate libraries the library the House Peers the library the House Representatives both which were established the creation Japans Imperial Diet 1890 and the Imperial Library which had been established 1872 under the jurisdiction the Ministry Education The Diets power prewar Japan was limited and its need for information was correspondingly small The original Diet libraries never developed either the collections the services which might have made them vital adjuncts genuinely responsible legislative activity Until Japans defeat moreover the executive had controlled all political documents depriving the people and the Diet access vital information The occupation forces under General Douglas MacArthur deemed reform the Diet library system important part the democratization Japan after its defeat World War 1946 each house the Diet formed its own National Diet Library Standing Committee Hani Gor Marxist historian who had been imprisoned during the war for thought crimes and had been elected the House Councillors the successor the abolished House Peers after the war spearheaded the reform efforts Hani envisioned the new body both citadel popular sovereignty and the means realizing peaceful revolution The Occupation officers responsible for overseeing library reforms reported that although the Occupation was catalyst for change local initiative preexisted the Occupation and the successful reforms were due dedicated Japanese like Hani The National Diet Library opened June 1948 the presentday State GuestHouse former Akasaka Detached Palace with initial collection 100000 volumes The first Librarian the Diet Library was the politician Tokujir Kanamori The philosopher Masakazu Nakai served the first Vice Librarian 1949 the NDL merged with the National Library previously called the Imperial Library and became the only national library Japan this time the collection gained additional million volumes previously housed the former National Library Ueno 1961 the NDL opened its present location Nagatach adjacent the National Diet 1986 the NDLs Annex was completed accommodate combined total million books and periodicals The Kansaikan the Kansai Library which opened October 2002 the Kansai Science City Seika Town Sraku County Kyoto Prefecture has collection million items May 2002 the NDL opened new branch the International Library Childrens Literature the former building the Imperial Library Ueno This branch contains some 400000 items childrens literature from around the world Though the NDLs original mandate was research library for the National Diet the general public the largest consumer the librarys services the fiscal year ending March 2004 for example the library reported more than 250000 reference inquiries contrast recorded only 32000 requests for research from the National Diet Japans national library the NDL collects copies all publications published Japan Moreover because the NDL serves research library for Diet members their staffs and the general public maintains extensive collection materials published foreign languages wide range topics The NDL also has eight major specialized collections Modern Political and Constitutional History Materials Concerning the Postwar Occupation Japan Laws and Preliminary Records Science and Technology Maps Music Foreign Books About Japan and Rare Books The Modern Political and Constitutional History Collection comprises some 300000 items related Japans political and legal modernization the 19th century including the original document archives important Japanese statesmen from the latter half the 19th century and the early 20th century like Hirobumi Iwakura Tomomi Sanj Sanetomi Mutsu Munemitsu Terauchi Masatake and other influential figures from the Meiji 18681912 and Taish 19121926 periods The NDL has extensive microform collection some million pages documents relating the Occupation Japan after World War This collection include the documents prepared General Headquarters GHQ and the Supreme Commander the Allied Powers SCAP the Far Eastern Commission FEC and the United States Strategic Bombing Survey Team The originals these documents are the possession the United States National Archives The Laws and Preliminary Records Collection consists some 170000 Japanese and 200000 foreignlanguage documents concerning proceedings the National Diet and the legislatures some foreign countries and the official gazettes statutes judicial opinions and international treaties pertaining some 150 foreign countries The NDL maintains collection some 530000 books and booklets and million microform titles relating the sciences These materials include among other things foreign doctoral dissertations the sciences the proceedings and reports academic societies catalogues technical standards etc The NDL has collection approximately 440000 maps Japan and other countries including the topographical geological and hydrological maps and charts dating back the early Meiji period 18681912 and topographical maps foreign countries The NDL collects all phonographic recordings made Japan and presently holds collection comprising 300000 vinyl records and 200000 compact disks Following the tradition established the Imperial Library the NDL collects foreignlanguage materials about Japan including rare and ancient documents such reports European missionaries visiting Japan the 16th century The NDL houses the former Imperial Librarys collection Japanese language materials from the Edo period 16031867 and earlier periods The major catalogues this collection include some 6000 documents relating the Tokugawa shogunate 16031867 such records town magistrates the shogunal Supreme Court and the Commissioners Shrines and Temples well documents concerning the succession shguns the Bunko and Shirai Bunko consisting 8000 handwritten and woodblock printed books dating from the Edo and Meiji periods and concerning Japanese medicine and the Shinjo Bunko consisting 11000 examples premodern writings astronomy and calendars addition ancient Chinese works the Qing dynasty genealogy and local history Kansaikan Kansai Library which opened Kyoto Prefecture 2002 the second facility the NDL The NDL has transferred the following collections the Kansaikan most western periodicals books and other materials nonJapanese Asian languages certain scientific and technological materials technical reports papers foreign academic societies catalogs Japanese and foreign technical standards foreign doctoral dissertations and conference proceedings Western languages scientific research reports compiled under grants from the Ministry Education Culture Sports Science and Technology Japanese doctoral dissertations and books tape The National Diet Library has recent years compiled detailed website both Japanese and English Its online databases consist the National Diet Library Online Public Access Catalog NDLOPAC National Diet Library Digital Collections and the Minutes the Imperial Diet and National Diet The NDL provides Online Public Access Catalog OPAC which users can search the NDLs entire collection from anywhere the world either English Japanese Using OPAC identify sources and catalog numbers overseas users may obtain certain materials from the NDL through interlibrary loan addition the NDL provides feebased reproduction service for scholars residing overseas June 2017 NDLOPAC planned end the end December 2017 and new online services will launched NDL Digital Collections provices various online materials such rare